<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-586-282  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 586 282.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer  June 1990 v23 n6 p106(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Transferring technology is tough. (the transfer of softwaretechnology is discussed at the 12th International Conference onSoftware Engineering in Nice, France)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Myers, Ware.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The mechanisms of the transfer of technology, particularly viablebut underused software technologies, was the focus of the'Experience Using Defined Processes for Technology Transfer' panelat the Mar 26-30, 1990 - 12th International Conference on SoftwareEngineering in Nice, France.andP;  The discussion was exemplified by aproblem addressed by another panel, the difficulty indissemination of efficient formal methods of software developmentthrough the software community.andP;  Presentations addressed suchsubjects as the frequent insufficiency of conventional transfermechanisms, the need for a collaboration between thoseknowledgeable about a technology and 'receptors' who know whereand how it will be deployed, and the central importance ofproactive management in implementing successful technologytransfers.andP;  Metrics are deemed important to determining transfersuccess.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Technology TransferConferencesIEEEImpact Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>